{
  "title": "Formation of Power on a Ship",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "06577e5f01ab41ba",
      "text": "A ship cruises from port to port in the eastern Mediterranean, goods of all kinds and passengers of all tongues on board, merchants and tourists on their way to the next market or temple, family visitors, transients, fugitives. Most camp out on deck. The only luxury and at the same time the only props of the following plot are some deck chairs. There were about a third as many as passengers.\nIn the first days, between three or four ports,\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0edcd678dfcbac8b",
      "text": "In the first days, between three or four ports, these deck chairs constantly change hands. As soon as someone stood up, the deck chair was considered free. Slip symbols were not recognized. This exercise became completely accepted and proved to be expedient. The number of deck chairs was about enough for the particular need, one could usually find one if one wanted. A commodity that was available in limited numbers was not in short supply.\n\nAfter leaving a port where passengers had changed as usual, this order suddenly broke down. The new arrivals had taken possession of the deck chairs and claimed permanent ownership. They therefore declared even a deck chair that was temporarily not occupied by them as \"occupied\". This was still not enforceable by occupancy symbols. But it succeeded by the common effort of all Auch owners: If one approached a just free deck chair in any suspicious way, one was rejected by poses, gestures and shouting of the Auch owners. The deterrent actions were so impressive that a physical conflict did not occur. Moreover, in the course of time they were reinforced by the fact that the owners moved their deckchairs closer together, until finally concentrations arose that resembled fortified wagon castles. The deck chairs that were not occupied at the time were folded up and served as a ring wall.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fa8786df7eb3e7f1",
      "text": "After the assertion of exclusive powers of disposal of a subgroup over a generally coveted commodity, the hodgepodge of passengers took on structure. Two classes had established themselves, the haves and the have-nots, the positively and the negatively privileged. If one compares these two new subgroups with the totality of passengers who had participated in the earlier order, it immediately becomes apparent that what was really original about the new order – at least in its first phase – was the establishment of negative privileges. One subgroup was denied access to a commodity. The privileged subgroup, on the other hand, could use this good as needed, that is, just as everyone had before. Assuming that their needs remained the same, they had not yet gained any advantage over the former entirety. The enviable aspect of their situation lay in the fact that they did not belong to the others. Further however above all in the expandability of its position. It takes little imagination to predict the further course of events if the journey continued for a while under the same conditions.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f4f675361debb6b5",
      "text": "The next step is undoubtedly the temporary rental of the deck chairs to some non-owners. As a counterpart, in addition to goods in kind, mainly services come into question, and here again primarily the assumption of that function which arises with every claim of ownership, the function of the guardian. The delegation of the guardianship to some non-possessors not only brings a real relief to the possessors, it also leads to a further enrichment of the inner structure, which can now unfold in three parts: in the groups of the possessors, the guardians and the only-propertyless. At the same time, an essential clarification is achieved: The only-propertyless are from now on in the worst position by their own free will and fault.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0549f26bc6a8ab01",
      "text": "We are only repeating the standard question that must always and everywhere impose itself on this last group when we consider how this could happen. The process is clearly against the will of the majority, the result is unfavorable for the majority. It does not have to go that way, but it can - as everyone knows - go that way. The minority, absurdly enough, has a chance to impose its new order. How, in what is this chance founded?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7a368180b9501c47",
      "text": "Even a first consideration shows that an open show of force, a tangible conflict, would have been most dangerous for the minority in the first phase, in which it asserts its claim to ownership and thus a division of the whole into two parts. Once the tripartite division has been established with the formation of a service class, then in the case of an open trial of strength it is already no longer certain who would actually be in the minority. So we will concentrate on the first phase for the time being. What peculiar potencies can the minority bring to bear to get through this first phase?\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e431b04ed6d21e12",
      "text": "I. The superior organizational capacity of the privileged.\nWe can leave open here when the newcomers came to an agreement about their claim to property. That it was a solidarity group from the outset, some family clan, is expressly not to be assumed. At a certain point in time, a series of quarrels must have revealed that two opposing ideas of order were in conflict with each other on the ship.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f6e4a832ab8e343c",
      "text": "We can leave open here when the newcomers came to an agreement about their claim to property. That it was a solidarity group from the outset, some family clan, is expressly not to be assumed. At a certain point in time, a series of quarrels must have revealed that two opposing ideas of order were in conflict with each other on the ship. Those who derived permanently exclusive powers of disposal from an act of \"occupation\" that had already been carried out claimed an advantage. They were thus already privileged in their self-interpretation, – by virtue of well-acquired rights. Their opponents did not claim this privilege for themselves, but denied it in principle.\nFor the time being, it is still clear who will be in the majority. But it is already questionable what weight majority relationships have. Comparing the two groups reveals a difference that is much more essential: the privileged have the greater chance of organizing quickly and effectively. Their common interest is not necessarily more intense, but more organizing.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "66e89b51dc11e4cd",
      "text": "First of all, think of a most simple circumstance. If I wish that a deck chair which I temporarily occupy should not be occupied by others in my absence, but voucher symbols are not recognized, there is only one thing I can do at first: ask another person to supervise it, to represent my claim. This other person, however, is in this first phase inevitably an also-lounger, my neighbor. Only he can have an interest in helping me. But his interest is also unusually fevident: first, he can hope that I will help him in the same situation, and second, every case in which a possessory claim achieves validity promotes its own chances. Mutual support, cooperation, thus imposes itself immediately. By helping the other, we help ourselves and the principle at the same time."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "923c7810d24c7c69",
      "text": "The cooperation is necessary: I cannot preserve a possession on which I cannot constantly sit without outside help. Cooperation is obvious: The possessors have something to offer each other directly: Substitution, protection, confirmation. Individual and common interest coincide. This relationship becomes immediately obvious and relevant for action. The new recliners had to quickly figure out their need and ability to organize.\n\nThe situation of the non-owners is much more complicated. In themselves, the commonality of interests seems obvious here as well. But as soon as an attempt is made to translate it into action, it becomes questionable. The only thing that cannot be doubted is the interest in ousting the propertied classes. But this first step is problematized from the second. What should happen if a common action would be successful? How will the newly conquered deck chairs be disposed of? The expectation of driving out the possessors does not give any security for the individual to achieve anything for himself. The agreement that the existing order is unjust does not yet create an agreement as to which new order would be just. Agreement that the existing order is just, on the other hand, equates agreement as to what new order would be just with – namely, none.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e1d7f7dfc388091f",
      "text": "In our case, the obvious solution for the dispossessed seems to be the restoration of the former order, i.e. a mere right of use without permanent claims. However, this obvious solution is at the same time the most difficult and the most improbable one under the given circumstances. The one-time recapture of the deck chairs would by no means be sufficient to enforce the principle of inheritance as long as the opposing group insists on its claims. They could occupy and defend the deck chairs again and again. In the free competition of the two designs of order, the advocates of the pure right of use would have to assert themselves anew each time against fixed claims of ownership, while they, for their part, would release the deck chairs after use without conflict. Consequently, the conflict situation would manifest itself every time they were the have-nots. \"Free competition\" would mean nothing else for them than that they could be constantly maneuvered back into the situation of the attacker and disturber of the peace – with nothing more in their hands than their principle. The conclusion is not new: The representatives of the cooperative egalitarian principle can only prevail if they assert themselves radically. Either they must succeed in suppressing possessive thinking in such a way that it cannot practically come into effect – the \"re-education\" – or they must form a closed society in which the others do not participate, are excluded from the right of use. The result is that strange compulsion to intolerance which seems to be inherent in a certain conception of order, but which arises merely from the relationship between two conceptions of order. Rules of free competition inevitably create unequal chances for the conflict of these ideas of order. Those who are against \"having\" cannot compete freely with those who want to have."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "35fe90d8a568211a",
      "text": "On our ship, the restoration of the old order was unlikely because the attempt was either futile (in the case of free competition) or (in the case of exclusion of the others) would have been \"too radical\" – a very typical alternative. But if the dispossessed attack haphazardly or only with the intention of turning the tables, then the problem of redistribution arises immediately and predictably for everyone. As soon as some of the hitherto dispossessed sit on the newly conquered deck chairs (as soon as some of the landless have staked out the occupied land for themselves), they are faced with the question of whether they cannot personally consider the distribution problem settled and thus the action completed. The idea of non-possession, of the pure right of use, has probably lost its innocence by now. But it is not enough for everyone anyway. The first success thus separates the attackers into groups with at least latently different interests. This difficulty of holding out immediately after the first occupation, however, is only the beginning of a chain of similar conflict situations. Their common core is the fact that the attackers bring the distribution problem, which the defenders have solved for themselves, into the conflict. They inherit it, as it were, from the status quo they are fighting."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "c685dc95e62c11b7",
      "text": "This burden is, as I said, predictable. Before we join with other dispossessed people in a common action, we ask ourselves what is in it for us. The answer is vague or risky. Mutual aid – cooperation in conflict actions – does not yet ensure individual success. Cohesion is not immediately rewarded for the individual; commonality initially means only a gamble. What the dispossessed really have to offer each other is decided only later. Solidarity is therefore dependent on all participants orienting themselves towards the next but one phase. The willingness to organize must be constituted not on a momentary advantage, but on a distant goal, not on the real, but on the imaginary deck chair. It can be founded only on a speculative confidence, on a speculative solidarity, – an incomparably much higher achievement than is expected of the privileged.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "68fbe89d47179921",
      "text": "But the formation of such trust is further complicated by specific opportunities for manipulation on the part of the privileged. The privileged are able to constantly compete the hope of future benefits with the offer of present benefits: in the form of material rewards for service and loyalty, opportunities for relative individual advancement. (Why shouldn't I help guard deck chairs if I can use them temporarily to do so?) We know this strategy from all stratified societies. It does not establish the inhibitions to organizational capacity of the negatively privileged, but further reinforces them.\n\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9be7d473367f1d69",
      "text": "These inhibitions are, of course, surmountable. But for the negatively privileged, much stronger impulses are needed to reach the level of organizational capacity that is almost self-evident for the positively privileged. The mere willingness to act – the \"determination to act\" – does not achieve the balance. The solidarity-based willingness to act with staying power that is necessary for this obviously requires above all a \"disproportionality\" of objectives and hopes. Utopia (in the sense of this \"disproportionality\") seems to be the realistic method to meet the speculative character of the required solidarity. The deficit of organizational capacity is compensated by a realism of a different kind."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1b2cffbf074e7189",
      "text": "On our ship, too, a curiously large internal and external effort would have been necessary to eliminate the new order. Curiously large, because here the claim of a minority asserts itself. Curiously great because an advantage falls, as it were, into the laps of the new deckchair owners – the opportunity for cooperation that presents itself – while the non-owners are suddenly faced with an unusual difficulty in translating what everyone wants into something that everyone wants.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "a6bc0cd058f799b6",
      "text": "To David Hume's question why the few seem to rule so easily over the many, the first answer would be: Because and insofar as the few are the possessors, and because possession – the defense of possession, the solved problem of distribution, and thus the consensus of order – conveys a superior organizational capacity. They rule not least because they are superior in this way, and because they rule they can constantly reproduce and possibly further extend this superiority. There are, of course, countervailing processes as well: For example, what we call \"democratization\" today is essentially the product of an organizational capacity of the basic class, quite exceptional by historical standards, which emerged anew in the course of industrialization. To inquire into the reasons for such gradual changes is a task in itself. In our case it turns out that the \"additional chance\" of the superior organizational ability already arises in the status nascendi of a power formation: The new group initially possessed nothing but the instantaneous de facto disposition of a general commodity and laid claim to exclusive and permanent power of disposition: this seemingly razor-thin advantage was sufficient for the formation of a superior organizational capacity, – and thus for the beginning of a process of accumulation of power against the interests of the majority.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "998d3b6c4c5843a2",
      "text": "2. The emergence of legitimacy from the principle of reciprocity.\n\nThe path to the further expansion of power is probably largely mapped out: a part of the negatively privileged majority is brought into direct dependence, drawn into the relations of wage-performance or protection-obedience (creation of a service class). This later phase will be examined in more detail following the second and third examples. Here we shall first be interested in a phenomenon which can already be observed in the beginning of the formation of power and which also contributes to the explanation of the absurd assertiveness of the new group: a process which one could call the generatio aequivoca of legitimacy.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fa39aee15c67abf2",
      "text": "In Max Weber's sense, an order, and in particular an order of rule, achieves legitimacy if it is recognized as \"binding in itself\"; a recognition of a fundamental kind that goes beyond mere habit and opportunity and creates an additional motive to behave in accordance with this order. With the degree of legitimacy, therefore, the chance of behavior conforming to the order or to the rule increases. Now Max Weber sees this legitimation always in a social vertical, as it were: as a relationship from bottom to top or from top to bottom. The rulers make a legitimacy claim downward, the ruled address a legitimacy belief upward. This is a useful simplification for representing formed legitimacy structures. But it can mislead if one asks about the emergence of the legitimacy regime, about the first discernible traces of this process.\n\nOn our ship, a new order gradually developed that privileged a particular group. For whom did this new order first become legitimate, how did a legitimacy rule form here? The answer is as simple as the question. Initially, this order appeared legitimate to the privileged themselves. But not simply in the sense that each of them believed in himself, in his own claims and well-acquired rights. Rather, recognition took place according to the principle of reciprocity in a process of exchange among the privileged. This is decisive. Just as they helped each other out of evident interest in defending their claims, so they helped each other in building up their convincingly good conscience: I recognize not only my claim, but also the claim of the other who recognizes mine. – Because I acknowledge the other, I am in the right; because the other acknowledges me, he is in the right. – Because the other recognizes me as I recognize him, and I him as he recognizes me, our claims are grounded in our right.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "f3d443564e7eeb9e",
      "text": "The validity of legitimacy is thus initially formed in a social horizontal, as a mutual confirmation between equals, as a consensus of the privileged about the validity of the order that privileges them. Social barriers are initially precisely not to be overcome. It is an internal process within the group of primary legitimacy stakeholders."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "e7ef87dd2f2511be",
      "text": "\nThis internal process, however, not only gives increasing security to the participants, it also has a radiating effect: the suggestive power of agreement. As is well known, the strong conviction that something is right and just is enormously contagious anyway; if this conviction emanates from groups, as a certainty that has already become social, the power of suggestion is intensified. This does not necessarily presuppose that the group explicitly appeals to others, that it turns outward in a demanding manner. The suggestive power of agreement already works when the internal mutual recognition process becomes visible, observable for others: for example, in the demonstrative ceremonial of the privileged, which \"pretends\" legitimacy, symbolized in a representational behavior (forms of greeting, clothing, gestures of recognition with their prefigurative effect)."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fc6f7a330e112cf8",
      "text": "In our case, however, it did not go so fine. The mutual recognition of the privileged had a militant appeal character, it was directly connected with the demonstration of common readiness to defend. But here, too, the process of the successive spread of legitimacy becomes more comprehensible if one realizes that the legitimacy-granting confronts the \"others\" in an already formed, self-confident, consolidated form."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3f6560ae89766908",
      "text": "Before the legitimacy validity reaches its actual goal - as a legitimacy belief in the social vertical from the bottom to the top - it is always already there in a developed form (even a coercive rule is always legitimate in this sense before the \"actual\" legitimacy process even begins). This is another peculiar additional opportunity that arises for its actors already in the first phases of the formation of power: the internal construction of that consciousness that offers motives of docility beyond habit and interest. Here, too, a power potency accumulates as if by itself."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "cd07f8fe1ab95079",
      "text": "\nThe mutual recognition of the privileged, moreover, is not only the first phenomenon of the legitimacy development of a new order. It can also - as the last vestige preserved by an old order - long outlast the de facto collapse of \"its\" order. The European nobility is a clear example. Here, too, the remnants of a legitimacy validity are still preserved above all in the internal exchange process of recognition. This process of exchange develops a continuing force of its own. In the last as in the first stage, it seems to radiate a certain suggestive effect to the outside, rather than being dependent on external confirmations."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "e73ddf1e68bae171",
      "text": "~"
