      "type": "edit",
      "id": "fa8786df7eb3e7f1",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "fa8786df7eb3e7f1",
        "text": "After the assertion of exclusive powers of disposal of a subgroup over a generally coveted commodity, the hodgepodge of passengers took on structure. Two classes had established themselves, the haves and the have-nots, the positively and the negatively privileged. If one compares these two new subgroups with the totality of passengers who had participated in the earlier order, it immediately becomes apparent that what was really original about the new order - at least in its first phase - was the establishment of negative privileges. One subgroup was denied access to a commodity. The privileged subgroup, on the other hand, could use this good as needed, that is, just as everyone had before. Assuming that their needs remained the same, they had not yet gained any advantage over the former entirety. The enviable aspect of their situation lay in the fact that they did not belong to the others. Further however above all in the expandability of its position. It takes little imagination to predict the further course of events if the journey continued for a while under the same conditions.\n\nThe next step is undoubtedly the temporary rental of the deck chairs to some non-owners. As a counterpart, in addition to goods in kind, mainly services come into question, and here again primarily the assumption of that function which arises with every claim of ownership, the function of the guardian. The delegation of the guardianship to some non-possessors not only brings a real relief to the possessors, it also leads to a further enrichment of the inner structure, which can now unfold in three parts: in the groups of the possessors, the guardians and the only-possessors. At the same time, an essential clarification is achieved: The only-possessors are from now on in the worst situation by their own free will and fault.\n\n"
