        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "66e89b51dc11e4cd",
        "text": "First of all, think of a most simple circumstance. If I wish that a deck chair which I temporarily occupy should not be occupied by others in my absence, but voucher symbols are not recognized, there is only one thing I can do at first: ask another person to supervise it, to represent my claim. This other person, however, is in this first phase inevitably an also-lounger, my neighbor. Only he can have an interest in helping me. But his interest is also unusually fevident: first, he can hope that I will help him in the same situation, and second, every case in which a possessory claim achieves validity promotes its own chances. Mutual support, cooperation, thus imposes itself immediately. By helping the other, we help ourselves and the principle at the same time.\n"
