      "date": 1665861953905
    },
    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "c685dc95e62c11b7",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "c685dc95e62c11b7",
        "text": "This burden is, as I said, predictable. Before we join with other dispossessed people in a common action, we ask ourselves what is in it for us. The answer is vague or risky. Mutual aid - cooperation in conflict actions - does not yet ensure individual success. Cohesion is not immediately rewarded for the individual; commonality initially means only a gamble. What the dispossessed really have to offer each other is decided only later. Solidarity is therefore dependent on all participants orienting themselves towards the next but one phase. The willingness to organize must be constituted not on a momentary advantage, but on a distant goal, not on the real, but on the imaginary deck chair. It can be founded only on a speculative confidence, on a speculative solidarity, - an incomparably much higher achievement than is expected of the privileged.\n\nBut the formation of such trust is further complicated by specific opportunities for manipulation on the part of the privileged. The privileged are able to constantly compete the hope of future benefits with the offer of present benefits: in the form of material rewards for service and loyalty, opportunities for relative individual advancement. (Why shouldn't I help guard deck chairs if I can use them temporarily to do so?) We know this strategy from all stratified societies. It does not establish the inhibitions to organizational capacity of the negatively privileged, but further reinforces them.\n\nThese inhibitions are, of course, surmountable. But for the negatively privileged, much stronger impulses are needed to reach the level of organizational capacity that is almost self-evident for the positively privileged. The mere willingness to act - the \"determination to act\" - does not achieve the balance. The solidarity-based willingness to act with staying power that is necessary for this obviously requires above all a \"disproportionality\" of objectives and hopes. Utopia (in the sense of this \"disproportionality\") seems to be the realistic method of doing justice to the speculative character of the necessary solidarity."
      },
      "after": "35fe90d8a568211a",
      "date": 1665861959858
