    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "fa39aee15c67abf2",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "fa39aee15c67abf2",
        "text": "In Max Weber's sense, an order, and in particular an order of rule, achieves legitimacy if it is recognized as \"binding in itself\"; a recognition of a fundamental kind that goes beyond mere habit and opportunity and creates an additional motive to behave in accordance with this order. With the degree of legitimacy, therefore, the chance of behavior conforming to the order or to the rule increases. Now Max Weber sees this legitimation always in a social vertical, as it were: as a relationship from bottom to top or from top to bottom. The rulers make a legitimacy claim downward, the ruled address a legitimacy belief upward. This is a useful simplification for representing formed legitimacy structures. But it can mislead if one asks about the emergence of the legitimacy regime, about the first discernible traces of this process.\n\nOn our ship, a new order gradually developed that privileged a particular group. For whom did this new order first become legitimate, how did a legitimacy rule form here? The answer is as simple as the question. Initially, this order appeared legitimate to the privileged themselves. But not simply in the sense that each of them believed in himself, in his own claims and well-acquired rights. Rather, recognition took place according to the principle of reciprocity in a process of exchange among the privileged. This is decisive. Just as they helped each other out of evident interest in defending their claims, so they helped each other in building up their convincingly good conscience: I recognize not only my claim, but also the claim of the other who recognizes mine. - Because I acknowledge the other, I am in the right; because the other acknowledges me, he is in the right. - Because the other recognizes me as I recognize him, and I him as he recognizes me, our claims are grounded in our right.\n"
      },
      "date": 1665863221849
    },
