    {
      "type": "edit",
      "id": "f3d443564e7eeb9e",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "f3d443564e7eeb9e",
        "text": "The validity of legitimacy is thus initially formed in a social horizontal, as a mutual confirmation between equals, as a consensus of the privileged about the validity of the order that privileges them1. Social barriers are initially precisely not to be overcome. It is an internal process within the group of primary legitimacy stakeholders.\n\nThis internal process, however, not only gives increasing security to the participants, it also has a radiating effect: the suggestive power of agreement. As is well known, the strong conviction that something is right and just is enormously contagious anyway; if this conviction emanates from groups, as a certainty that has already become social, the power of suggestion is intensified. This does not necessarily presuppose that the group explicitly appeals to others, that it turns outward in a demanding manner. The suggestive power of agreement already works when the internal mutual recognition process becomes visible, observable for others: for example, in the demonstrative ceremonial of the privileged, which \"pretends\" legitimacy, symbolized in a representational behavior (forms of greeting, clothing, gestures of recognition with their prefigurative effect).\n\nTranslated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
