    {
      "type": "add",
      "id": "cd07f8fe1ab95079",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "cd07f8fe1ab95079",
        "text": "\nThe mutual recognition of the privileged, moreover, is not only the first phenomenon of the legitimacy development of a new order. It can also - as the last vestige preserved by an old order - long outlast the de facto collapse of \"its\" order. The European nobility is a clear example. Here, too, the remnants of a legitimacy validity are still preserved above all in the internal exchange process of recognition. This process of exchange develops a continuing force of its own. In the last as in the first stage, it seems to radiate a certain suggestive effect to the outside, rather than being dependent on external confirmations."
